segments.text: Sounds like you had a lot of duties, a lot of responsibilities.
How were they?
At Twethler?
Yeah.
Oh.
Well, I had essentially the same types of forces under me that I'd been supervising within my responsibility in Southeast Asia.
F-105, fighter bombers.
groups, special action forces, special service forces, staff forces, troop carrier forces.
Essentially, well, tactical air command and tactical air warfare are the same.
My responsibilities
were, I had the responsibility.
I wasn't a deputy or assistant.
I had the responsibility.
I was the boss.
And I told you geographic, area-wise, to what extent.
And my job, of course, was training these horses and keeping them, keeping, maintaining their training.
Keeping them supplied, maintained, and combat ready as possible.
And of course, continued to
provide the replacements in their various categories from officers and airman skills over to Vietnam would reject where I came from.
So, you know, I had, I was well qualified, exceedingly, terrifically well qualified to take over my job.
Sounds like it'd be a much, I don't want to, well it sounds like a,
an easier or a smoother operation than in Vietnam.
It doesn't sound like in Thailand.
It doesn't sound like as many problems.
Is that true?
Well, oh, considerably different from the standpoint of pressure and the hectic and the, for instance, the realization that I've got to be available right by my command post 24 hours a day.
And to a certain extent, you know, I...
Gee, the insurgent might attack my base right now.
That type of thing.

Now, from the standpoint of responsibility for the morale of my people, the responsibility of seeing if they're properly trained, I mean, properly fed, properly the bases taken care of, the aircraft properly supplied and maintained, exactly the same.
Were there any main challenges that you had in terms of the 12th?
As a matter of fact, there was no problem.
As a matter of fact, I enjoyed it.
It was a relaxation to come back and go down there, of course.
I think the biggest wasn't a challenge.
to move my headquarters down to Berksham Air Force Base in Austin, Texas.

And, of course, I continually and closely supervised that, including the construction and layout and planning of a brand new building, if you will, a mini Pentagon building, except this was an oval shaped building, dictated to a great extent by the President of the United States.
Oh, really?
I was going to ask, why did you move from Waco to Austin?
Well, first of all, I'm sure that entered into it, probably primarily, but see, we didn't have a base as such at Waco.
I just had a flight section out at old James Connolly Air Force Base, which used to be a training area.
permanent air force base.
It's permanent.

And band power-wise and expense-wise, it would cut expenses to consolidate my headquarters on a tactical basis, Berkson being primarily a reconnaissance-equipped base, a reconnaissance wing there, and get rid of the Wake Oaks hood.
It saved money, so it made sense.
But it was done, and it so happened that I laid out all the plans and was prepared to actually move in September when within a month's time I decided to retire.
Okay, now this might sound like a silly question to someone who's not in the know about air bases, but why didn't you go down to San Antonio and move down there?
Because they have such facilities down there.
Well, San Antonio was overburdened at the bases with logistic organizations, and there was no room for my headquarters to be down there.
And tactically, it didn't make sense.
It ought to be on one of my air bases.
And actually, economics-wise, the United States, and politics-wise, San Antonio has got, you might say, more than its share of military population.
LBJ came out to honor you.
Tell me about that.
That was on one of his, you mean at Bergstrom?
Yeah.
That was on one of his, the presidential trips to his home where, you know, he'd take vacations.
Quite often, his ranch.
And he always landed at Bergstrom.
But it so happened that through the channels down through, and of course the Air Force provided the American administration all the time.
Really, he provided the crews for his number one.

But I was to receive an honor for being one Air Force in the entire United States that had sold the most bonds, had most bonds purchased by airmen and officers from any Air Force in the United States.
Therefore, I was being awarded a pennant called an E-Pennant or something.
A flag.
I guess that's what you call it, yeah.
And of course it was quite an honor and I was going to accept it.

So arrangements were made way up above the top of me when President Johnson come down, why not let's have him present this flag to you and be, and I'm sure he wanted to do it because, you know, give him a chance to be amongst the military as well as the citizens of Austin.
He agreed with it, so that's the reason it was done.
And he personally, this was all laid on, when he landed, I agreed with him naturally.
And then all this, the airfield was flooded with the Austin civilians.
Press corps.
Oh, absolutely.
And then he, in fact, TV and radio, and he presented me this flag.
And then made a short speech about how he was proud of the military and also the city of Austin and so forth.
Very well received, and I consider it quite an honor.
What was your opinion of Johnson?
I liked him.
I liked him.
Even though you're a conservative, you told me before.
That's right.
About three days ago.
I agree, but he... Why did you like him?
I think he had a sincere feeling for his fellow man.
And he was kind of an easy... Maybe other people would call him a smoothie, but I...
He was easy talking.
I met him once before and greeted him in Thailand at this huge bomber base down in southern Thailand, you know, when he came over.
And he was the same way, easy going, easy talking.
In other words, a typical good old fellow with a Texas grow, if you will.
I liked him.
He was just personable, all very, very.
I know for a fact that he could be a different man.
I heard stories where, boy, he just literally ate out you-know-what of the Joint Chiefs of Staff for not doing better in the war in Southeast Asia.
Couldn't understand why with all the equipment that they had and so forth.
Okay, now, during this time, during 1968, of course, we had the Tet Offensive in Vietnam on January 31, 1968.
here at the 12th Air Base.
And by 1968, there were anti-war protesters in the United States.
And I was wondering if you ever had any protests outside your headquarters, or on the base, or had any dealings with this whatsoever.
No, I can't remember ever having a problem at any of my bases with protesters.
Did you have any problems whatsoever with any civilians?
No.
As a matter of fact, every base, this is one thing I pushed, was social relations with the communities where we were based.
And I always gave high priority to this, and our base commanders easily understood this.
I don't remember ever any occasion where I had a problem of that nature.
And at Waco,
It just broke the hearts of those people when we had to move.
The mayor and the councilman and all that.
Let's change the topic now to advancement in the military.
We've touched a little bit on this before.
You said that you were an ambitious man in the military, right?
No more ambitious than the average one.
But I call myself ambitious, yeah.
Okay.
Thinking back on the military career, though,
Did you leave advancement, promotion, to fate or luck, or did you think that you had control over your own advancement?
Oh, there's no doubt that such a thing as luck
Right, right.
There's no doubt there's such, maybe quite fate, but there's no doubt that there's such thing as that in our life.
But I sure agree that every person has a certain amount of control over what he can do.
I definitely agree with that.
Is that primary or is fate?
Primary on what?
Our fate.
Which one's more important?
Oh, your...
Don't depend on luck.
On accomplishments.
Right.
Okay.
Do you think, what about advancement as far as the military?
We might have talked about this a little or talked around it a little.
The military advancement, do you advance the same way that somebody get ahead in the military, get a command position in the military the same way that you do in business or the professional world?
Are there differences?
In my opinion,
I am glad you asked that.
Because you've been in both of them.
Right.
You've been in TI.
I was ten years at TI right after I got out of the Air Force, retired.
As a matter of fact, I even stood up and told my bosses and the chairman of the corporation right on down at TI, there ain't no difference whatsoever.
Some things are basic.
Some things are basic.
And what were those basics to you?
Capability is one thing.
Anybody recognizes capability.
Number one, though, in my opinion, is integrity.
Integrity.
Can you trust a person?
Is he reliable?
Will he tell you the truth?
Will he tell you he's made a mistake?
Will he tell you that what I'm recommending to him, that it's a bad idea?
Will he be a yes man?
Can I depend on it?
Is he reliable?
Integrity, I'm talking about.
You know why.
Absolutely.
Which is honesty.
Right.
And I'm sure any military man and any civilian corporate official.
As a matter of fact, it so happens that Fred Busey of Texas Institute, the chairman, executive president of TI, puts this as his number one requirement for an executive at TI.
Integrity?
Yes, sir.
And obviously, capabilities.
Can the man, is he capable, is he competent?
Okay, now, you've been in both the business world at a high level and in the military world at a high level.
Do they think, do people out in society think differently?
In other words, is there what some people have called a military mentality?
Have you heard that term, military mentality?
Oh, yeah, I've heard that.
Would you define it?
Is there one?
Well, I tell you what I think civilians mean when they say you have a military mentality.
I think they mean that you're regimented.
You're regimented.
You're told what to do.
You're used to being this.
You're disciplined to a rut, if you will.
You have no flexibilities.
Now, you think, you don't think flexibly, and this is absolutely nonsense.
The current officer, in my opinion, even more so now than in my earlier days, he has to be equally as capable as any manager of a corporation you can think of.
You compare my salary
As the Air Force commander of 12th Air Force commanding some 45,000 people with, let's say at the time I joined Texas Instruments with the president of TI at that time, Mark Sheppard, who is now the
chairman of the board with his salary and about the same number of people, say, in 1968.
Maybe not that many, maybe 30,000 people.
Compare their salaries.
Yeah, he probably made fringe benefits and salary included.
He probably made four times as much as I made in dollars.
You'll get the argument, yeah, but you don't have a budget control over you.
That's not true.
That's nonsense.
You don't have to perform efficiently as I do.
I get fired.
Remember me telling you about the fear of the way psych control people?
Sure.
I have fired people.
I have fired people under me.
I was told by TR... For being incompetent?
Well, incompetent, mainly, yeah.
Not telling me truth.
Mainly not doing a job.
So we've covered that military mentality.
You don't believe there is one, sir?
There used to be.
There used to be.
Oh, how did this change?
What do you mean, there used to be?
Oh...
Before the war?
I remember when I joined the National Guard as a private in 1932.
You talk about a regimented man, yeah, but the quality of the man then was not what it is now.
Remember me telling you about the Air Force establishment system by which I got to go to college.
We want our officers with college degrees.
Look at the retirement of General Hay, who is now the Secretary of State, a few months ago.
Look at the civilian job he had and was given.
The chairman of, what is it, United Technologies.
And look at the money he was immediately paid.

As a matter of fact, I remember in the later years of my military career, some, I think it was Chief of Staff, General McConnell or probably generals before him, Chief of Staff, making speeches throughout that

And certainly taught at the Air Force Academy, by the way, an instancy had been 10, 12 years ago, 15 years ago, that an officer nowadays had to be a manager, had to be a diplomat, had to be a chaplain, had to be an officer.
You name it, he had to be all of them.
Do you think this has changed because of the tremendous growth in the American armed services since the Second World War and the increase in importance?
Right, and the integration into the way of life of the modern power of the nature of the United States.
And armed force reflects, its people reflects,
the, if you will, the culture and status and nature characteristics of its civilian population.
It reflects it directly.
Okay.
Now let's shift to why you retired.
Why did I retire?
This was really an emotional, it was a problem of mixed emotion.
I've been in the service since, I've been in the military, like I've told you in previous discussions the last two or three days, since 1930, during the high school ROTC as a buck private.
I've been in two wars.
I was content and happy with my
progress or the achievement of a historic general.
I was still ambitious.
I had no doubt in my mind I could go on higher.
No doubt in my mind.
A military, I mean.
Were you called out?
No.
By, oh, well, officers told me, sure.
In their disgust, yeah, it's implied.
But you know, you feel, you know, any guy does, unless you kid yourself.
I knew that inevitably my next job had to be, had to be, almost without a doubt, the Pentagon, which I certainly did want.
Or probably vice commander of TAC, which did have been a promotion, probably both of them went to promotion.
And I'd been vice commander of some jobs before, a number two man.
I could relax.
Well, I never relaxed no matter what job I had.
Sure.
So I'd been given some thought to it.
Say I was tired from war coming.
Well, that's not true.
See, I had a year, I had time to relax here.
I had a 12th Air Force.
I was a commander.
Everybody shoots for a job.
I had an ideal job, and I was happy.
Didn't have any problems, no worries, except what you have ordinarily, data.
But I think the Starbroke Camelback is a- They're eating out.
Okay.
My wife just came in and I was going to talk about it.
Okay, well tell me this and then we'll eat.
The Starbroke Camelback is my wife got sick and it was obvious she had to have a- Hysterectomy.
Hysterectomy.
It was, as I say, we didn't have an air base or any military facility there, so... Medical facility.

Medical facility, so we had to go to a local civilian doctor in Waco and a hospital, well-equipped hospital, and the doctor took care of her, and she was scheduled for surgery, and she had a hysterectomy.
Unfortunately, within about 24 hours, she had an abdominal block, intestinal block,
And I'm convinced today through sloppy procedures.
And she had to be rescheduled for emergency operation again by another doctor.
And it was nip and tuck for a few hours.
But fortunately, she recovered and lived.
But it was some tense moments I went through.
really made me think and I just came to the conclusion that I dragged my family and her all over the world.
We moved some 26 times in about 22 years.
I made up my mind I was going to retire and try to live a restful life in retirement and enjoy it and try to enjoy life with her.
and still had two of my four children living with us.
So I made the decision, decided to write a letter.
And I remember General McCollum was still chief of staff at that time.
General Diss's way, I told him about it, he was absolutely caught completely off guard.
And Diss, he said, Charlie, you don't mean it.
He was surprised.
He didn't expect it whatsoever, because he was doing a fine job under him.
And he said, well, you have to tell General McCollum to write a letter so I can get it.
What you want to do?
I told him the whole story.
And knowing him now.
You told him this his way the whole story?
Oh, yeah.
And the trick man.
He knew.
He understood.
Matter of fact, he retired.
So happy he retired the day after I did.
But I wrote a letter to General McConnell and to his deputy chief of staff personnel, Lieutenant General,
I can't remember his name by now, whom I know very well.
He called me on the telephone and said, John Charles, you've caught General McConaughey.
General McConaughey, I'm mad at you.
I said, well, I, this was one of the things I was worried about, but I said, I, sincerely, I assure you I wouldn't do it unless I thought it was the proper thing to do.
I know General McCollum gave me this job, and I appreciate it all, and I just hope you can explain it to him, and I'd be more than happy to come up and sit down and try to question him.
He said, no.
He said, if you want to, he told me, he said, if you want to, go ahead and retire.
He said, he'll prove it.
So it was laid on, and I retired August 1, 1968.
I cried.
Was it a nice ceremony, and did they have a big review for you?
Oh, yeah.
Matter of fact, general discipline came down.
No kidding?
Yeah.
And then he went out for his own retirement the next day?
And I got on the airplane to Flying Bay and left his retirement.
Oh, you did?
Yeah.
And then didn't you tell me that the next day after that you started at Texas Instruments?
Officially, I was put on the payroll at TI the next day.
Mm-hmm.
That is not the primary reason I retired.
Oh, no.
I didn't infer that.
I'm just saying that you had things to look forward to.
As a matter of fact, that's one of the things I was looking forward to, realizing the capability of the TI, seeing what they had done.
I had to basically go up there and did promote the development of technology at TI, and they've done wonders.
What was your title at TI?
We're not going to get into it.
They didn't know for a while.
Matter of fact, I found out after about six months they were going to make me administrator of a special, no, administrator of a weapons system group.
But it turned out I was a marketing specialist.
I forget actually what the title would be, but it was primarily
Marketing for the equipment group, which is oriented primarily to the military, R&D and development of military equipment.
Sure.
OK, let's stop.
Could you define leadership for me?
No easy things.
Just like that, huh?
Define leadership.
I guess if you tried to define it in a classical sense in the term of a dictionary, I'd say probably the best way to define it is
The ability to get people to do what you want them to.
But this needs further explanation.
Many times, though, I've been asked this question.
I ought to be able to tell you right now, but you know you always think about it.
And I'll probably get around to ask a lot of rambling moments and what I've always said.
That's funny.

I usually try to think of it in terms of the people I've been under and who are the most effective ones from the standpoint of getting me to do what they want me to do, that they wanted me to do for them.
All the leaders I've told you that I wonder, you know, where his thinking is.
In other words, the guys I hated, the guys I loved.
Okay, the guys I loved probably had more leadership than the guys I hated.
You know, that type of thing.
So my reasoning process and analysis to answer your question.
I think the main ingredient in leadership is a natural
characteristic of a person to get along with people, generally speaking, to get along with people.
And to me, this means he knows how to handle people.
If he can handle a truculent type of a maverick and get him to do well under him, then he knows how to handle people.
If he can get a gold brick to perform under him, then he knows how to handle people.
The ability to handle people.
And rapidly, right underneath that, maybe that's not a number one thing, and maybe I'm not looking at priorities right now.
Let's talk about that.
Sure, we're just talking about characteristics.
But readily, the next thing that comes to me, just what I was telling you about a while ago, is integrity.
Integrity of a man.
This goes as well up.
respect for your boss or consideration for your subordinate down.
If your subordinate respects you and knows you're telling them that you're honest and respects your integrity and knows you've got integrity, he's going to respect you.
To me, integrity again.
Integrity is so basic in everything.
And the third element, I would say, a very important factor is your capability and competence in the area of which you are a commander.
In other words, can you do what you expect your people to do?
And here again, as I go back to old General LeMay, he flew combat in B-17.
In the roughest time, as a leader, he was a leader.
People knew he knew what he was talking about.
He'd been there.
That's right.
You've been there.
You know what you're talking about.
Don't tell me you can't do it, son.
I've done it.
Do it.
Not necessarily in that tone of voice, but it's that expectancy, both on the part of your subordinate and on the part of your commander.
You expect
a man to do it.
But see, that includes integrity also.
You trust and respect and rely on him to do it.

But he knows that you can do it, and this gives credence to the belief of the subordinate that this man, my commander, wouldn't tell me to do this unless he knew that I could do it, unless he knew that it could be done because he's done it.
And this readily leads into the next one, which I'd say is motivation.
If you can motivate, the capability to motivate, inspire, which is essentially the same thing.
Sure.
You can motivate a man.
T.I.
was great in the business world of using the word motivation.
You know, it's how you entertain and inspire.
I think in the military...
You could use the word motivation, but inspiring a man under you to do it.
I think it's an even more meaningful word.
We're inspired by heroes.
People have done things.
You motivate for it, but you're inspired by a hero.
You could be motivated by a ruthless, mean individual.
You know you better do it because you're scared to death.
You could be motivated by a very meek, incompetent officer begging you practically, gee, I can't do this.
Look, you've got to get this done for me.
I'm going to be in trouble.
You've got to get it done.
You can be, you know, subordinate, might be motivated that way.
But it's neither one of these I'm talking about.
I'm talking about a sincere, just an inherent in the situation, an inherent capability of the commander, the leader, that he motivates people.
He motivates them by his appearance, by his personality, by his manner of speaking, his experience, what he's been through.
Maybe the ribbon's on his chest.
Maybe he doesn't even have a tunic on, but his personality is such.
He inspires belief in him.
It's effect on people.
Sure.
Motivation.
These are all different types of, in other words, we're defining leadership by the type of values that a leader should have.
Well, that's right.
Because that's the other question I'd like to ask the generals.
And you've talked about being competent.
having integrity, being respectful of others, being able to handle people, being able to motivate.
I mean, these are sort of values.
These are values, I say, that make for leadership.
That's what I'm trying to find leadership in.
What are the characteristics of good leadership?
OK.
Personally, what type of these values did you have?
I tried to have them all.
You know, everybody, you, know your weaknesses and strengths better than anybody else in the world, whether you admit them or not.
I've often told my kid, be honest with yourself, recognize your strengths and weaknesses.
That really brings up probably a fifth or sixth one I can pass on to you right now, what I think of leadership.
And I give credit to Eisenhower for not teaching me this, but learning it from reading about him and experiences about him.

I think one of his greatest characteristics and traits that had been said of him, and I agree, and look at the job he did, and you talk about my job as different bosses and different types I had to deal with.
Look at his ability to pick people under him to do a job.
You're feeling about a person.
I want that man.
You're readily, an immediate assessment of a person.
I want this type of person under me.
Your recognition, immediately, of the capability of the person.
You know a good man when you see him.
I think this is one of Eisenhower's greatest capabilities.
He knew how to pick the right type of person.
Therefore, he eliminated a lot of his problems.
Okay, that's one of his great characteristics as a leader.
Another one about Eisenhower, and there's no doubt about this, is that he was a conciliator.
He had the ability to
work with people with very large egos, like Churchill, and Roosevelt, and Monty Montgomery, and Patton, and get them all to work for a common goal.
Right.

And it surprises me, sir, that you haven't brought this out about yourself, because in almost every position that you had from Italy all the way to Thailand, you were working with some pretty egotistical,
Pretty high-powered people, and you were trying to keep them to work together.
Don't you think that's part of leadership?
Well, I mentioned you're a conciliator.
Well, yeah, you could.
Is this not covered by ability to handle people?
Sure.
You know, can you handle your boss?
Sure you can.
You don't speak of it in that term, but you can handle your boss.
And you put it in other words, and it's a better understanding of what I'm trying to say.
I agree with you.
And conciliatory has the... You're a compromiser.
I mean, you compromise people.
To me, that's a better word.
Conciliatory has the connotation of...
Appeasement.
You're stepping down.
I'm not talking about that.
No, no.
Compromise, I guess, is involved.
It's involved in conciliation.
Obviously it is.
You manage two different... You were...

I don't want to put words in your mouth, but it seems like when you were working between the Ambassador in Laos and Westmoreland, here you are as you're trying to get people to work in a common direction.
Manage differences for a common goal, or consolidate differences for a common goal.
Influencing people to do what you know has to be done.
And furthermore, getting it done with a little fuss and
What about the use of punishment in the military?
Certainly, especially enlisted men get into problems.
Many of these people, young, relatively uneducated, away from home for the very first time sitting on an air base in Thailand, something like that, get out of hand, get a little rowdy.
It's only natural for anybody who's 19.
What were your ideas on punishing these people, maintaining discipline?
Well, you've always got to, it's not only military, but life.
You've got to have punishment, and we probably always will.
Everybody isn't perfect.
There's always going to be those, and you've got to have a means.
That is understood, generally, also.
The more it's understood and known, the better, more effective it'll be.
If you do certain things, you're going to be punished.
Now, the level of punishment, this is, boy, what a controversial thing.
The more universal and uniform you can have rules of punishment, by far, the better they are.
You've read today, it may... Less arbitrary.
Well, yes, but...
Look how the rules vary throughout the United States and civil courts, between judges.
You read of it every day.

And this is, you must strive to make it universally applicable, where if some new man comes to your outfit, and let's say he either intentionally or unintentionally does something, he knows what the consequence is going to be.
It's going to be the same.
is where he came from, or else he'd be completely the other side of the world.
Therefore, a certain amount of punishment must be set out in rules and regulations.
It's got to be so that they can be better distributed and understood.
But the main thing about punishment, in my opinion, is it's got to be equitable and it's got to be as expeditiously applied as possible.
The longer you wait, the less effective it is, and the harder it is to apply.
It's got to be immediate, as immediate as possible.

Now, if you were going to Texas A&M, and you were asked by the Commandant of the Corps to come and give a talk to these 18-, 19-, 20-year-old corpsmen about how to become a leader, what would you say?
I would think I'd probably outline in general, just like I've been talking to you, and then go back and expand on each one of the points and point out examples, and then summarize and recap again.
And then point out people like Eisenhower and LeMay that were exemplary of these particular characteristics of leadership.
In other words, try to improve on the values that you've already discussed.
Right.
I guess that's your...
I guess the way I'm defining leadership for you is I've given you characteristics of a leader.
In other words, these values.
Sure.
And who knows to say which one is number one and number two and three and four?
I don't know.
It depends on the particular circumstance where one might be more valuable.
Sure.
I tell you one that it's probably a little bit of a combination of the ones we've already mentioned in general, but you have an individual under you.
Naturally, all of us have weaknesses and strengths.
But you've got an individual you've got to use.
And here again, it's like I went back to, it's partly this capability.
Eisenhower, I think, had picked out the type of person he wanted to give the job.
I dare say he had a certain job for that man that he wanted him to do when he picked him out, maybe a staff man or a commander.

But to know as much as possible or at least have the capability to recognize by some means quickly the strengths and weaknesses of a man and to put him in a place where you use his strengths and his weaknesses, never have a chance to come to the surface and appear.
If he's a cook, use him as a cook.
If he's a mechanic, use him as a mechanic.
If he's poor at budgeting and financing, don't put him in a finance area, accounting area, that type of thing.
In other words, find out the skills of your men and then use them appropriately.
I think this goes without saying, but sometimes we don't do it.
And sometimes in the...
bureaucracy of large organizations, you've often heard, geez, they trained me to do this, and look where they sent me.
Now, I can understand.
I've been to business with 45,000 people under me.
I can understand how this gets lost in the cracks.
But generally speaking, the more a leader permits this to occur under his command, I think, well, the more he's asking for trouble.
The more trouble he has, the poorer leader he is.
